0.1 The Human Equation

Behind every proportion stands a consciousness that sought to describe harmony.
The compiler of Soyga, whether monk, scholar, or visionary, understood that numbers are mirrors of the mind.

The 32 Ã— 32 lattice reflects the structure of perception itself: expansion, rotation, and balanceâ€”the Fibonacci, Ï€, and Ï† of thought.

To decode Soyga is therefore to decode the observer.
Each reader becomes one more node in the pattern, completing the manuscript by their act of attention.
The missing thirty-third table is not lostâ€”it is you.


---

0.2 Continuity

This project forms part of a continuum that links Renaissance natural philosophy to modern information science.
The same logic that animates digital code can be glimpsed in these ancient grids.
Where Dee and his contemporaries spoke of angels, we now speak of algorithms;
where they invoked divine light, we speak of data.

Yet the essence remains unchanged: a faith that order exists and can be known.

Future research may extend the present reconstruction with spectral analysis of ink composition, cross-language frequency comparison, or simulation of the tables in dynamic time.
Every new method will reveal another facet of the same geometry.


---

0.3 Gratitude

This work owes its existence to patience shared and guidance unseen.
To those who encouraged its completion, to the custodians of libraries who preserve fragile manuscripts, and to the companions whose belief outlasted fatigueâ€”thank you.


